Housing Subsidies in Emil City

Chris Michael

November 1st, 2022

A. Introduction

The Motivation for Analysis

This study is an initial step aimed towards assisting the Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) of Emil City, in their approach to target home owners who qualify for a home repair tax credit program. The uptake of the home repair credit has been low, despite the efforts put in by the HCD to attract eligible home owners. This study aims to help streamline the department’s limited resources by converting all the client-level data collected from previous campaigns into a decision-making analytic, that can predict whether or not a homeowner will take up the housing subsidy. It is important to note that this study can be used as a primary base for further research, but cannot be used at this stage for policy and decision making.

C. Emil City Data

I. Exploring the Housing Data

Here are some average characteristics of homeowners who are eligible to take the tax credit program from the Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) of Emil City. This section visualizes predictive features by dividing it into continuous and categorical variables. Some of the variables of interest were the age of homeowners, their employment status and type of employment, as well as their marital status.

The density line plot showing the average of continuous features was interesting to look at compared to the barplots as it gave a more in depth view into the various categories of homeowners that were likely to take the credit. For example, homeowners over the age of 40 seemed to be inclined to take the credit, compared to others.

The barplots of categorical variables also show that with an increase in levels of education, there is an increase in the likelihood of a homeowner taking the tax repair credit. The same can be said for homeowners working in administrative, blue collar and technician jobs- as they seem to be more inclined to take the credit compared to people working in other sectors. There also seemed to be a higher rate of married homeowners willing to take the credit- which can potentially be attributed to the presence or lack thereof, of family households.

II. Feature Engineering

In order to develop a model to predict likelihood of taking home repair credit, I feature engineered a few variables from the initial table that were likely to increase the accuracy of my model. Some of the new variables were employment status, educational status and marital status.

housing <- housing %>%
  mutate(EmploymentStatus = case_when(job == "student" | job == "unemployed" |
                                        job == "retired" ~ "unemployed", 
                                      TRUE  ~ "employed")) %>%
  mutate(MaritalStatus = case_when(marital == "single" | marital == "divorced"|
                                     marital == "unknown" ~ "unmarried",
                                   TRUE ~ "married")) %>%
  mutate(EducationStatus = case_when(education == "illiterate" |
                                       education == "unknown" ~ "illiterate",
                                     education == "basic.4y" | 
                                       education == "basic.6y" |
                                       education == "basic.9y" |
                                       education == "high.school" ~ 
                                       "high school",
                                     TRUE ~ "university")) %>%
  mutate(Tax = case_when(taxLien == "no" | taxLien == "unknown" ~ "no",
                         TRUE ~ "yes"))

D. Statistical Modeling

I. Binomial Logit Regression Models

For this section, I created two datasets:

  • The dataset with the feature engineered variables

  • The kitchen sink dataset with just the initial set of variables

This is where we first start to see differences between the two datasets. After running the logit regression, the model with the engineer variables had a McFadden R-squared value of 0.22. However, the kitchen sink model had a McFadden R-squared value of 0.23, which is slightly higher that the engineered model. Any additions of both engineered variables or additional variables from the dataset seemed to further worsen the model.

set.seed(3456)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(housing$y_numeric, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)

housingTrain <- housing[ trainIndex,]
housingTest  <- housing[-trainIndex,]

housing_model1 <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data=housingTrain %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-y, -marital, -X,
                                  -education, -taxLien),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

Kable_1 <- pR2(housing_model1)


set.seed(3456)
trainIndex_ks <- createDataPartition(housing$y_numeric, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)

housingTrain_ks <- housing[ trainIndex,]

housing_model2 <- glm(y_numeric ~ .,
                  data=housingTrain_ks %>%

II. Making Predictions

From the density plots below, we can say that both the model with engineered features as well as the kitchen sink model, predict true negatives well; i.e, the number of people who do not take the credit. However, both models predict poorly for the true positives or the number of people that actually take the housing repair tax credit. These models can be bettered using additional variables like income, rent and poverty rates in the area.

testProbs <- data.frame(Outcome = as.factor(housingTest$y_numeric),

III. Confusion Matrix

The confusion matrices below show the slight differences between the kitchen sink model and the engineered model. Despite similar sensitivity and specificity values, the engineered model predicts one less true negative that the kitchen sink model. It also predicts true positives slightly worse than the kitchen sink model. In the 50% threshold, the engineered model predicts 27 occurrences of homeowners taking the housing repair credit, whereas the kitchen sink model predicts 29.

However, the engineered model seems to do better than the kitchen sink model in certain aspects: the number of false positives and false negatives are slightly lower than the predictions of the kitchen sink model.

In this particular section, the kitchen sink model is definitely recommended over the engineered one. This is because the kitchen sink model exhibits better sensitivity (true positives) and better specificity (true negatives), in the 50% threshold.

testProbs <- 
  testProbs %>%
  mutate(predOutcome  = as.factor(ifelse(testProbs$Probs > 0.5 , 1, 0)))

cm <- confusionMatrix(testProbs$predOutcome, testProbs$Outcome, 
                       positive = "1")

draw_confusion_matrix <- function(cm) {

  layout(matrix(c(1,1,2)))
  par(mar=c(2,2,2,2))
  plot(c(100, 345), c(300, 450), type = "n", xlab="", ylab="", xaxt='n', yaxt='n')
  title('Confusion Matrix: Engineered Model', cex.main=2)

  # create the matrix 
  rect(150, 430, 240, 370, col='#788211')
  text(195, 435, '0', cex=1.2)
  rect(250, 430, 340, 370, col='#8d634a')
  text(295, 435, '1', cex=1.2)
  text(125, 370, 'Predicted', cex=1.3, srt=90, font=2)
  text(245, 450, 'Actual', cex=1.3, font=2)
  rect(150, 305, 240, 365, col='#8d634a')
  rect(250, 305, 340, 365, col='#788211')
  text(140, 400, '0', cex=1.2, srt=90)
  text(140, 335, '1', cex=1.2, srt=90)

  # add in the cm results 
  res <- as.numeric(cm$table)
  text(195, 400, res[1], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(195, 335, res[2], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(295, 400, res[3], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')
  text(295, 335, res[4], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white')

  # add in the specifics 
  plot(c(100, 0), c(100, 0), type = "n", xlab="", ylab="", main = "DETAILS", xaxt='n', yaxt='n')
  text(10, 85, names(cm$byClass[1]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(10, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[1]), 3), cex=1.2)
  text(30, 85, names(cm$byClass[2]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(30, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[2]), 3), cex=1.2)
  text(50, 85, names(cm$byClass[5]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(50, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[5]), 3), cex=1.2)
  text(70, 85, names(cm$byClass[6]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(70, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[6]), 3), cex=1.2)
  text(90, 85, names(cm$byClass[7]), cex=1.2, font=2)
  text(90, 70, round(as.numeric(cm$byClass[7]), 3), cex=1.2)

  # add in the accuracy information 
  text(30, 35, names(cm$overall[1]), cex=1.5, font=2)
  text(30, 20, round(as.numeric(cm$overall[1]), 3), cex=1.4)
  text(70, 35, names(cm$overall[2]), cex=1.5, font=2)
  text(70, 20, round(as.numeric(cm$overall[2]), 3), cex=1.4)
}  

draw_confusion_matrix(cm)

IV. ROC Curve

The ROC curve helps us understand the goodness of fit of a model and the area under the curve (AUC) is a direct measurement of the curve. For the model with engineered variables, the area under the curve is 0.78, whereas for the kitchen sink model it is 0.77. For the engineered model, 0.78 represents the probability of getting a positive where there was a true positive. From the graphs, it can be observed that while the model predicts correctly 75% of the time, the model will also predict incorrectly 25% of the time, which is not a negligible number.

auc(testProbs$Outcome, testProbs$Probs)

A <- ggplot(testProbs, aes(d = as.numeric(Outcome), m = Probs)) +
  geom_roc(n.cuts = 50, labels = FALSE, colour = "#788211") +
  style_roc() +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, size = 1.5, color = 'lightgrey') +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve (Credit Model)",
       subtitle = "Engineered Model\n") +
  theme_minimal()

E. Cross Validation

I. Cross Validation & Generalizability

To understand generalizability, we run 100-fold cross validation and look at the ROC (aka AUC), Sensitivity and Specificity across this series of predictions. From the set of plots below, we can see that both the model with engineered features as well as the kitchen sink model generalize well when it comes to sensitivity- predicting true positives. Both models however, do poorly when it comes to specificity- predicting true negatives.

F. Cost Benefit Analysis

I. Calculations

Here are some of the given facts that will help guide the cost/benefit analysis in the upcoming sections.

  • If it is predicted that a householder will take the credit, then HCD allocates $2,850 per homeowner which includes staff and resources to facilitate mailers, phone calls, and information/counseling sessions at the HCD offices.

  • We should now assume 25% of contacted eligible homeowners receive the credit. The remaining 75% that receive the marketing allocation and enter the program do not take the credit for various reasons.

  • The credit allocates $5,000 per homeowner which can be used toward home improvement.

  • Homes surrounding the repaired home see an aggregate premium of $56,000, on average.

Therefore, the cost/benefit analysis is conducted as follows:

  • True Negative: Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated TN = 0

  • True Positive: Predicted correctly homeowner would take the credit, marketing resources were allocated, and 25% took the credit TP = ((58150 x Count)0.25)*

  • False Negative: Predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did FN = 0

  • False Positive: Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit, allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated Count(-2850)

The cost/benefit table is given below.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
                case_when(Variable == "True_Negative" ~ Count * 0,
               Variable == "True_Positive" ~ (58150 * Count)*0.25,
               Variable == "False_Negative" ~ ( Count * 0),
               Variable == "False_Positive" ~ (-2850) * Count)) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "Predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated, and no credit was allocated",
              "Predicted correctly homeowner would take the credit, marketing resources were allocated, and 25% took the credit",
              "Predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did",
              "Predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit, allocated marketing resources; no credit allocated")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

II. Optimizing the Cost/Benefit Relationships

The plots below are of trade-offs, showing revenue for each confusion matrix by threshold. The graphs show that the lines seem to tighten after hitting the 25% threshold mark. Our model predicts better for households in this range, and allocating resources to homeowners between the 25% and 100% threshold might help streamline resources and produce better outcomes.

whichThreshold <- 
  iterateThresholds(
     data=testProbs, observedClass = Outcome, predictedProbs = Probs)

whichThreshold <- 
  whichThreshold %>%
    dplyr::select(starts_with("Count"), Threshold) %>%
    gather(Variable, Count, -Threshold) %>%
    mutate(Revenue =
             case_when(Variable == "Count_TN"  ~ Count * 0,
                       Variable == "Count_TP"  ~ (58150 * Count)*0.25,
                       Variable == "Count_FN"  ~ (0) * Count,
                       Variable == "Count_FP"  ~ (-2850) * Count))
whichThreshold %>%
  ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Revenue, colour = Variable)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = col5) +    
  labs(title = "Revenue by Confusion Matrix Type and Threshold",
       y = "Revenue") +
  theme_minimal() +

III. Visualizers for Threshold

whichThreshold_v<- 
  whichThreshold %>% 
    mutate(TookCredit = ifelse(Variable == "Count_TP", (Count * .25),
                         ifelse(Variable == "Count_FN", Count, 0))) %>%
  group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(TotRevenue = sum(Revenue),
              TotCreditCount = sum(TookCredit))

G. Conclusion

From this study, it is clear that neither the neither the kitchen sink model nor the engineered model are fit to be used in a real world context just yet. Both due to the low McFadden R-squared statistic, low generalizability and low specificity, the model definitely needs some rigorous work as well as addition of new variables. When looking at homeowners who are eligible to receive the home repair tax credit, variables like income, rent, and what percent of income goes into rent and other housing related costs could be significant. Other variables of interest could include number of householders, place of work, if the household is already recieving subsidies from the government.

Some steps that could ensure that the marketing materials result in a better response rate could include streamline communications. Marketing materials that are accessible via a cellphone could open up information to wider audiences. Targeting new homeowners and informing them about the subsidies available could also be impactful. Lastly, targeting homeowners in the administrative, blue collar, management and technical sectors could also improve uptake of the credit.
